Preface: Classes represent real things and situations and you create objects based on these classes. Classes define general behavior of the object. An object from a class is instantiation and you work with instances of a class

__init__()
This method is special as it will run everytime regardless of class for any instance of the classs. When listing the parameters in the (), self must be included as this is how it will pass the variables.
__init__(self, v1, v2):
With this, we use self.v1 or self.v2 to move the data around the class. Different methods within the class will need the information from init() to build it

Example 1
class Human:
    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age

    def eat(self):
        print(f"{self.name} is eating.")

    def sleep(self):
        print(f"{self.name} is sleeping.")

human1 = Human("Alice", 30)

print(f"Subject for New Class")
print(f" Name: {human1.name}, Age: {human1.age}")

The output for this is:
Subject for New Class
Name: Alice, Age: 30

With lines 14-18 are methods defined and as long as parameters are set, such as in line 20, you can simply call the method

human1.eat()  # Output: Alice is eating.
human1.sleep()  # Output: Alice is sleeping.

By adding lines 31 and 32 after line 20, it will use that information and no new info will need to be added. This is how init() works, it saves the data input to give to all methods within the class

human2.eat()
human2.sleep()

As the class has the definition, you can reuse it with new information. Simply use a different variable to assign it to with the new information as in lines 36-37. Using them all together will give two new lines with Bob
instead of Alice

