                                                    Class Inheritance
Inheritance allows you to make a sub class that will take methods and parameters from the parent to use.
class Human:
    def __init__(self, name, age):
        self.name = name
        self.age = age
        self.workplace = "Office"

    def eat(self):
        print(f"{self.name} is eating.")

    def sleep(self):
        print(f"{self.name} is sleeping.")

    def work(self):
        print(f"{self.name} is working at {self.workplace}.")

class Child(Human):
    def __init__(self, name, age):
        super().__init__(name, age)
        self.school = "Elementary School"
    def play(self):
        print(f"{self.name} is playing.")

human3 = Human("Alice", 30)
human4 = Child("Bob", 10)

human3.work()
human4.play()

Lines 92-97 define the inherited class. 92 shows what is inheritaned, 93 is defining it.
Line 94 uses super(). to call the init() as super(). is a special fuction that allows you to call a method from the parent class. In this case, init is called which gives Child the same parameters in lines 79-81
A child class method can override a parent class method is they have the same name. However if the subclass has a overriding method defined and called, so long as the parent is called under its own variable,
it wont be overriden
